Where to go next.

You have taken the certification path, so let us look at the natural follow-ons. The biggest is kubernetes. After docker comes kubernetes, which orchestrates the very same images with a richer model and a far bigger ecosystem, and the mapping from notebook nine makes the transition concrete, a service becomes a deployment, a task becomes a pod, a stack becomes a chart. The kubernetes certifications come in a sensible order, an application-developer one focused on pods, deployments, services, and config, which is the right next cert after this one, then an administrator one focused on the cluster itself, and then a security specialist one on top of that.

If your work runs in a cloud, the cloud-vendor certifications make the platform-specific glue concrete, covering each provider's container services and usually bundled into their broader dev-ops or architect tracks. And there are adjacent areas of depth worth growing into. Continuous integration and delivery with containers, where the images you build actually reach production. Observability, the metrics, logs, and tracing you bolt onto containerised services to see what they are doing. Service meshes, which add layer-seven routing, retries, and mutual encryption between services. And the supply-chain tooling from notebook eight, taken all the way to production.

Step back and look at the arc. The path from I have never touched a container, back in notebook one, to I can architect a containerised production system with supply-chain attestations, multi-cluster failover, and a service mesh, is a real and walkable one, and you have completed the first half of it in this curriculum. The concepts you now hold, images and layers, the container lifecycle, storage, networking, composition, registries, security, and orchestration, are the durable foundation that everything above builds on. So go book the exam, and then keep climbing.
